				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">With the prospect of a guilty plea in the United States looming, the French bank BNP Paribas has enlisted the support of a powerful ally: its own government, including top regulators and the French president, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/02/french-officials-twist-u-s-arms-in-bank-inquiry">DealBookâs Ben Protess and Jessica Silver-Greenberg write</a></b>. President FranÃ§ois Hollande recently reached out to the White House to raise concerns about a plea deal, injecting a political undercurrent into a law enforcement investigation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">French officials have also contacted the State Department and the Treasury Department and <b>made direct appeals to the authorities investigating BNP</b>, emphasizing that the criminal case could have dire repercussions for BNP and the broader global economy. BNP is suspected of doing business with Sudan and other countries blacklisted by the United States. The French campaign has focused largely on the concern that <b>BNP might be required to suspend a core business</b> operation â processing transactions through its New York branch on behalf of foreign clients â as a result of the guilty plea.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>The behind-the-scenes arm-twisting</b> underscores the international implications of the BNP case, which has inflamed diplomatic tensions and pitted the French government against American authorities. Mr. Protess and Ms. Silver-Greenberg write: âAt the heart of the French governmentâs campaign is the concern that American prosecutors have created a <b>two-tiered system of justice</b>: one in which American and British banks escape criminal charges and the other that forces BNP to plead guilty to sanctions violations and pay a record fine.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">FOOD FIGHT, ROUND 3 <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Pilgrimâs Pride has raised its takeover bid for Hillshire Brands, turning up the heat in a battle over the maker of Ball Park hot dogs and Jimmy Dean sausages, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/02/pilgrims-pride-said-to-raise-bid-for-hillshire">DealBookâs Michael J. de la Merced writes</a></b>. The new offer, worth about $55 a share, tops a $50-a-share offer from Tyson Foods that was announced last week. The latest bid is 22 percent higher than Pilgrimâs Prideâs original unsolicited proposal, which was also announced last week.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Pilgrimâs Prideâs new bid values Hillshire at about $6.7 billion, while Tysonâs offer is worth about $6.1 billion. Both figures exclude the target companyâs debt. The dueling takeover offers lay the groundwork to <b>halt Hillshireâs own deal to buy Pinnacle Foods</b>, the maker of Birds Eye frozen vegetables, for $4.3 billion.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">FOR DRUGS OR MONEY <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> To the extent that J. Michael Pearson, the chief executive of Valeant Pharmaceuticals, has succeeded over the years, it has not been through innovation, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/02/do-drug-companies-make-drugs-or-money">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column</a></b>. Instead, Mr. Pearson has cut costs and arbitraged tax domiciles. Now, Valeantâs bid for Allergan, the maker of Botox, made alongside the hedge fund manager William A. Ackman, has raised a question: Is the role of leading pharmaceutical companies to make drugs or money?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Over the last several weeks</b>, Mr. Pearson and Mr. Ackman have criticized Allergan and its chairman and chief executive, David E. I. Pyott. But Allergan is far from deserving of such vitriol, Mr. Sorkin writes. He adds, âWhat weâre left with isnât a tale about a brilliantly innovative drug company trying to buy a mismanaged fixer-upper; itâs quite the opposite. Valeant, desperate for ways to increase its revenue, needs a cash cow to milk until it can find the next one.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Whatever Valeantâs reason</b> for wanting to acquire Allergan, the bid has been unconventional from the start, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/02/valeant-and-ackman-break-from-the-deal-playbook-yet-again">David Gelles writes in DealBook</a></b>. And on Monday, Valeant and Mr. Ackman broke from the deal playbook once again, abandoning plans for an informal shareholder referendum. Instead, the parties said they would seek a special meeting to elect a new Allergan board and were preparing a tender offer they could take directly to Allerganâs shareholders.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Data on <b>factory orders</b> for April is out at 10 a.m. <b>Esther George</b>, president of the Kansas City Fed, gives a speech on monetary policy at 1:50 p.m. Eastern time in Breckenridge, Colo. Tesla holds its annual stockholder meeting at 11 a.m. Pacific time in Mountain View, Calif. The Commodity Futures Trading Commissionâs <b>Technology Advisory Committee</b> holds a public meeting at 10 a.m. on issues related to high-frequency trading. Vice Admiral <b>Michael S. Rogers</b>, the director of the National Security Agency, is on Bloomberg TV at 3 p.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> TROUBLE AT SALESFORCE <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Nearly everything about Salesforce.com is remarkable, including its stock, which has risen more than tenfold in the last 10 years. But the company is also remarkable in another way â over the last decade, it has, in aggregate, produced no net income, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/02/falling-price-of-shares-creates-risk-at-salesforce">DealBookâs Peter Eavis writes</a></b>. Still, investors appear to have gotten comfortable with the companyâs red ink.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But in recent weeks, <b>a situation has been brewing</b> that could threaten Salesforceâs notable run. The trigger could be the recent decline in the companyâs shares that has wiped 20 percent off their value. Normally, a decline in the price of a stock has almost no effect on a companyâs financial results or the health of its core operations. But in the case of Salesforce, the falling share price could <b>expose the companyâs vulnerabilities</b> and directly affect its business performance.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Most technology companies</b> use a combination of stock and options to help pay employees. But Salesforce makes much greater use of stock-based compensation. A prolonged slump in its shares could set off negative reactions throughout the company that could ultimately <b>weigh on its sales and free cash flow</b>.</p>
</div>
